body: Hello - are your results correct though (despite the warnings) ?

Looks like a converter issue with Slice nodes. The 3 Slice nodes are claiming that the output shape matches the input shape. e.g. Slice_10, Slice_15 and Slice_20 all have input and output of shape {B, T} which is incorrect given the parameters to the Slice op. 

The output shape should be {B, 1} for Slice_10 and {B, T-1} for the other two. 

A symbolic name is assumed to only ever have one value. We re-use buffers where possible if the shape matches, and because of the incorrectly declared output shapes we are re-using a buffer. The warning happens when we see the actual shapes of the buffers don't match. As the re-use requires a smaller buffer we allow it, but it's just luck that the re-use requires a smaller buffer. 

How was the model exported? From pytorch?
Yes, it was exported from PyTorch. It traces a LogFilterBank frontend that does preemphasis and thus uses T-1 tensor as intermediate value. It seems to still work correctly, yes.
Sure, I can take a look. Thanks for your investigation.

Looks like there are some ONNX build issues meaning it could take awhile to get the fix PR merged and consume it in ONNXRuntime. I ll close this issue when the fix PR is merged in ONNX and consumed here.

Is it still onnxrt fault? Or is PyTorch to blame? This code just does some stft / audio frontend: https://github.com/vadimkantorov/convasr/blob/master/models.py#L337-L349 and onnxruntime complains about number of channels changing (?)

```python
import numpy, onnxruntime
# onnxruntime.set_default_logger_severity(0)
sess = onnxruntime.InferenceSession('model.onnx')
predict = sess.run(None, {'x': numpy.random.rand(1, 10000).astype(numpy.float32)})
```

@skottmckay should this issue be reopened?
@hariharans29 Could you please check https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/2756#issuecomment-646630674 ? I think this issue still persists...

The issue is that your model is using opset 10 and the fix was applied to the latest version of Slice (opset 11). Can you re-export the model using a later opset? 13 is the latest but not sure if pytorch supports that. Anything >= 11 should be fine. 

e.g. `torch.onnx.export(..., opset_version=11, ...)`
Will try! Thanks!
It seems to have helped! Case solved!

@vadimkantorov which opset_version worked for you? 
I tried with 12,13 but still got the same warning.
I think it was okay with opset==11, but a regression could have been introduced since that antique onnxrt version...

@vadimkantorov I got the same warning, I used opset_version = 16, but it will get an error when I changed opset_version = 11 
(error: RuntimeError: Unsupported: ONNX export of repeat_interleave in opset 9. Unsupported along dimension with unknown input size. Please try opset version 13.)
So I changed opset_version = 13, It will get this error: 
torch.onnx.symbolic_registry.UnsupportedOperatorError: Exporting the operator ::grid_sampler to ONNX opset version 13 is not supported. Support for this operator was added in version 16, try exporting with this version.

I don't know how to solve it, is it a problem of my model?
It's quite likely there is a regression... Maybe open a new issue or let's ask @hariharans29 and @gramalingam to reopen this one?
